@node "HowToInstall" "Installation"

@{MS "Installation"}

Just use the included installer script to install this application!@{par}

@{b}Don't try to install this archive by hand, because this may cause many trouble. The automatic installation
ensures a minimum use of disc and memory space!@{ub}

@endnode
@node "HowToUse" "How to use R?"

@{MS "How to use R?"}

I'll take the AmigaDos command "DIR" as exmaple. Of course it's working with
most other commands, too!@{par}

If you call: "dir ?" you'll see the following options within the CLI/Shell :@{par}

"DIR,OPT/K,ALL/S,DIRS/S,FILES/S,INTER/S:"@{par}

and if you're not an expert in reading @{"templates" link "FAQSTemplate"} you
may not try this with the "List" command.@{par}

That's the point "R" comes in. Press return to exit the dir command and type "r
dir".@{par}

Whow, as you can see the writing isn't more complicated than "dir ?". That's why
I gave the tool it's short name.:)@{par}

A @{"window" link "MAST"} is opening and all arguments of the
@{"template" link "FAQSTemplate"} are shown as gadgets.@{par}

If you have knowledge on @{"Templates" link "FAQSTemplate"} and their usage you
can append arguments for the "dir"-command right when calling "R".@{par}

R dir t: all@{par}

The "t: all" stuff will be handles as argument for the "dir"-command and the
gadgets in the window will be set up with that information.@{par}

If you save a profile for the "dir"-command by using the GUI, then you can set and override
those settings. E.g. you stored a profile where "DIR ram:" and "all" is set. If you call now "r dir inter"
this switch is also set when the GUI shows up.@{par}

Never try "R" without arguments! Just kidding. Running "R" without arguments
will cause "R" to create a GUI for "R". :)@{par}

It's also possible to create a project icon. As default tool just "r" and then
add a tooltype to specify the command to use by adding. e.g. "command = dir"
Optional you can specify default arguments for that command. e.g. "Arguments =
t: all". Now the command GUI opens with bedefined arguments. You may have asumed
that the "NOGUI" switch is working too as tooltype. Same for loading a
profile.@{par}

@endnode
