@node "FAQS" "Questions, Solutions and Tips!"

@{MS "Questions, Solutions and Tips!"}

@{jcenter}@{"What is a Template?" link "FAQSTemplate"}@{par}

@{jcenter}@{"I have a command that is not working! Why?" link "FAQSNOGO"}@{par}


@endnode
@node "FAQSTemplate" "What is a Template?"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "What is a Template?"}

A template is a preset. In AmigaDOS this preset is so genial, that it's more an
standardized manual.@{par}

To get a template simply call a command by appending a question mark. The copy
command would look like this:@{par}

Copy ?@{par}

FROM/M,TO/A,ALL/S,QUIET/S,BUF=BUFFER/K/N,CLONE/S,DATES/S,NOPRO/S,COM/S,NOREQ/S:@{par}

Each argument is separated by a "'".@{par}

Each argument has at least one keyword. By using this keyword the argument is
bind:@{par}

Copy FROM t:hello TO ram:@{par}

is identical with:@{par}

Copy TO ram: FROM t:hallo@{par}

Spaces are only allowed when being specified in brackets. Like this:@{par}

Copy "ram disk:hello" to t:@{par}

Some templates require such keyword. Like the BUF=BUFFER argument! The /K
informs the user that the keyword must always be specified before the argument.
In any other case the keyword are optional, but the arguments order is fixed.
Upper and Lower case doesn't matter. I just wrote them upper case to highlight
them.@{par}

BUF=BUFFER is also special. The "=" informs the user that "BUF" or "BUFFER" can
be used as keyword. Many commands are providing such short cuts.@{par}

The characters behind the "/" are also specifying the type of argument.@{par}

/K as I already told, the key word must be specified or the command will fail.@{par}

/A This argument must be specified. Without the command will fail.@{par}

/M This argument supports more than one sub arguments. For example the copy
command: Copy t:Hello t:World ram:@{par}

Since I don't used any keywords and the "TO/A" argument is required, the first
two arguments will be handled as "FROM" and the last as "TO" argument. Of course
it looks more understandable when providing the same call with key words:@{par}

Copy FROM t:Hello t:World TO ram:@{par}

/N This is a numeric argument. Only numbers and "-" are allowed.@{par}

/S This is a little special. This command just has it's keyword. If you specify
the key word the option is on. If the key word is not defined, the option is
off. It's a simple switch. If you use "CLONE" with the copy command this
function is active. In any other case it's not.@{par}

/T is working exactly like /S. It's just meant a toggle argument. Just take the
following template as example:@{par}

"ALLOFF/S,ALLON/S,1/T,2/T,3/T,4/T,5/T,6/T"@{par}

"ALLON 1" turns option 1 to 6 on and turned switch 1 off. "ALLOFF 1 4" is turning
all switches off, but 1 and 4 on." Well, this option is very rare.@{par}

/F is also kind of rare. It means "Final" and defines the last argument of that
command. Any specified argument (even with key word) isn't parsed and treated as
one single argument. As example you can use "R":@{par}

R dir t: all@{par}

The "dir" is the file name anything behind is handled as one argument. Funny is
that in this case the argument keyword is also named "arguments"!@{par}

@endnode
@node "FAQSNOGO" "I have a command that is not working! Why?"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "I have a command that is not working! Why?"}

The command used with "R" must provide a Commodore style
@{"Template" link "FAQSTemplate"}. When using the command and
specifying a "?" it should return something like this:@{par}

aaa/x,bbb/y,...,www/z:@{par}

Programs that are using a linux style or program specific argument can be
handled by "R".@{par}

If a program is starting, even if the argument is wrong, then this may cause
problems.@{par}

Example: ED " => ED is starting !!!@{par}

@endnode

@node "MAST" "The Main Window"

@{MS "General Window Functions"}

Underlined characters are short cuts.@{par}

If there is a pop up button behind a string input field, then shift and the
underlined character is activating the pop up gadgets.@{par}

Escape is closing the program. Pushing the window close button oder the cancel
gadget has the same effect.@{par}

Return is causing the command to be executed.@{par}

If you push the help key you'll get specific information on the gadget below the
mouse pointer.@{par}

Click @{"here" link "MainMenu"} to get information about the
@{"nenü" link "MainMenu"} attached to this window.@{par}
@{code}
@{MS "These gadgets are available"}

@{JCenter}@{"Text Input" link "MASTSTRI"}

@{"Numeric Input" link "MASTNUMB"}

@{"Switch" link "MASTCHBO"}

@{"Execute" link "MASTEXEC"}

@{"Cancel" link "MASTCANC"}

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@{"Main Window" link "MAST"} @{"R Preferences" link "Glob"}

@endnode
@node "MASTSTRI" "The Main Window - Text Input"
@toc "MAST"

@{MS "Text Input"}

Within the CLI/Shell spaces must be enclosed in brackets. Within "R" this isn't
required, because "R" is creating them for you.@{par}

Anyway /M arguments require the usage of brackets if you want to specify more
than one argument:@{par}

Argument                  -> converted to -> Argument@{par}
Argument 1                -> converted to -> "Argument 1"@{par}
"Argument 1" "Argument 2" -> converted to -> "Argument 1" "Argument 2"@{par}

Arguments with a "/M" marking also support file requester multi selection.@{par}

If the input field name is displayed bolded, then this argument is strongly
required ("/A") for correct command operation.@{par}

@endnode
@node "MASTNUMB" "The Main Window - Numeric Input"
@toc "MAST"

@{MS "Numeric Input"}

If the input field name is displayed bolded, then this argument is strongly
required ("/A") for correct command operation.@{par}

Only numeric characters (incl. "-" are allowed.@{par}

@endnode
@node "MASTCHBO" "The Main Window - Switch"
@toc "MAST"

@{MS "Switch"}

Setting the switch inside the GUI is like specifying the key word when using the
command in CLI/Shell.@{par}

@endnode
@node "MASTEXEC" "The Main Window - Execute"
@toc "MAST"

@{MS "Execute"}

The command will be executed with all specified arguments.@{par}

@endnode
@node "MASTCANC" "The Main Window - Cancel"
@toc "MAST"

@{MS "The Main Window"}

The "R" main window and all sub windows will be closed without any action.@{par}

@endnode

